Architecture plan for Issue #115: Harden server-render error handling for home and admin routes

Current structure:
- Public App Router pages live under src/app/(public), with the home route in src/app/(public)/page.tsx.
- Admin App Router pages live under src/app/(admin), with the admin dashboard in src/app/(admin)/admin/page.tsx.
- Database reads for the affected routes use the shared Prisma client from src/lib/db.ts.
- Reusable UI building blocks live in src/components; existing route-state-panel.tsx provides loading/error-style presentation patterns used elsewhere.

Planned module/file changes:
- Add src/app/(public)/error.tsx as a client route-level error boundary for public route render failures.
- Add src/app/(admin)/admin/error.tsx as a client route-level error boundary for admin dashboard render failures.
- Update src/app/(public)/page.tsx so getHomeData() catches Prisma/page-loader failures, logs a useful server-side message with the original error object, and rethrows so the new boundary handles display.
- Update src/app/(admin)/admin/page.tsx so getPosts(), getSubspaces(), and getTags() each catch loader failures, log route/function-specific context with the original error object, and rethrow so the admin boundary handles display.

Dependencies and sequencing:
- No issue dependencies; this is a single hardening issue.
- Error boundary files can be added independently, then loader logging can be patched route by route.
- Existing public/admin data shapes and Prisma queries should remain unchanged.

Key design decisions:
- Use Next.js App Router error boundaries with "use client" and reset() actions for recoverability.
- Keep changes focused: do not refactor page loaders or alter database query semantics.
- Log server-render loader failures with stable route/function labels plus the full unknown error object for production observability.
- User-facing error UI should avoid leaking internal database/error details while offering a retry control and navigation fallback.
- Preserve the existing AI News brand and page styling conventions.

Validation plan:
- Run npm run lint/typecheck if dependencies are available.
- Run npm test where feasible.
- Build validation should continue through prisma generate, next build, and cargo build for the Axum API.
